On Friday, Jon Lewis was sacked as head coach of England Women‚Äôs team and 24 hours later Heather Knight followed him out of the door.A 16-0, error-strewn whitewash in Australia required major changes and the ECB has certainly delivered on that score. Lewis was always unlikely to survive after his ‚ÄúBondi-to-Coogee‚Äù interview, when he blamed the defeat on Australia‚Äôs sunnier climes, made him a laughing stock. But stripping Knight of the captaincy is a far more radical step ‚Äì an admission that, despite the insistence to the contrary of Clare Connor, the managing director of women‚Äôs cricket, the ECB‚Äôs review has indeed uncovered evidence of a poor team culture. description: On this week's Stumped, Alison Mitchell, Brett Sprigg and Charu Sharmu discuss India‚Äôs dominance of the men‚Äôs white ball game - will it continue all the way through to next year‚Äôs T20 World Cup and beyond? It‚Äôs after India added the Champions Trophy to the T20 World Cup they won in Barbados last year. Virat Kohli reckons this current squad has enough talent to "take on the world" for the next eight years. We speak to Cricket Australia‚Äôs outgoing Chief Executive Nick Hockley. He‚Äôs standing down at the end of this month after five years in charge. He tells us the controversial resignation of men‚Äôs Test captain Tim Paine was one of the most challenging periods of his tenure, but that he and Paine have since spent a lot of time together and he backs him to have a long and successful coaching career.He also told us he believes support for the Afghanistan women‚Äôs team will continue after his departure and that the controversial decision to mark 150 years of England against Australia with a day/night game can celebrate the history of the game whilst also nodding to the future.Plus, we look at what Harry Brook‚Äôs decision to withdraw from the upcoming Indian Premier League means for him and England.Photo: Virat Kohli of India and teammate Rohit Sharma celebrate following the team's victory in the ICC Champions Trophy 2025 Final between India and New Zealand at Dubai International Stadium on March 09, 2025 in Dubai, United Arab Emirates.
